On 7/27/11 11:42 AM, vinoth_amaranathan wrote:
&gt; I&#39;m using heritrix 1.14.4 and the configuration file is included
&gt; below after the report.
&gt;
&gt; a) I would like to know why we have large number of snoozed queues
&gt; here and all threads waiting for jobs.

Snoozes in minutes are indicative that a &#39;retryDelaySeconds&#39; longer wait 
is in progress, after a fetch-failure that is indicative of some sort of 
network- or server-unresponsive situation, like a connection-timeout.

Usually it makes sense to wait a while for these to resolve (and space 
out the maxRetries over a longer period, so a few minutes&#39; transient 
server/network outage doesn&#39;t cause us to give up), and let other URIs 
be tried in the meantime. But, Heritrix doesn&#39;t have any facility for 
speeding these up when nothing else is waiting to be crawled.

&gt; b) How to reduce the wakeup time of the snoozed queues. These wakup
&gt; times seems longer.

The &#39;retry-delay-seconds&#39; setting (default:900) controls this long-wait, 
and the &#39;max-retries&#39; setting (default:15) controls how many reattempts 
will be made before treating the URI as definitively failed. (The 
max-retries should always be larger than 2 or 3, because the normal 
temporary-skipping-of-a-URI to get DNS or robots info can consume a 
couple of retries.)

&gt; c) How to increase the number of ReadyQueues. Is it configurable in
&gt; the xml ?

&#39;Ready&#39; means essentially &#39;not waiting out a politeness/error delay&#39; and 
&#39;not in the backlog of queues not being currently worked on&#39;. It&#39;s not 
something you can change directly; it&#39;s a quality of the queue state.

- Gordon
